Asset 1: POS (Toast)
Role: System of record for every transaction. The truth layer.
What it FEEDS to the dashboard:

Daily sales by daypart
Menu item velocity (units + revenue)
Order channel mix (dine-in / takeout / online direct / DoorDash / Uber Eats / Grubhub)
AOV by channel
Customer email captures (where prompted)
Loyalty member behavior
Catering vs retail split

What the dashboard DISTRIBUTES based on POS data:

Forecasted sales for tomorrow / next 7 days
Slow daypart alerts → triggers SMS/Email/Meta ads
Top-seller flags → triggers content (TikTok, GMB posts, ad creative)
Bottom-seller flags → triggers menu engineering review
Channel mix shifts → triggers margin protection moves (push direct ordering when DoorDash share grows)
New customer captures → triggers welcome series in email platform

Refresh cadence: Daily auto-export → dashboard. Weekly manual review.
Owner: GM or owner pulls every Sunday night.

Asset 2: Website (Google Search Console + Google Analytics 4)
Role: Visibility layer. Tells you who's finding you, what they search, and what they do once they land.
What it FEEDS to the dashboard:
From GSC:

Search queries Chicho's ranks for
Click-through rates per query
Average position (ranking) per query
Pages getting impressions vs clicks
Indexing status (any pages dropped from index?)

From GA4:

Sessions by source (Google, social, direct, paid)
Top landing pages
Conversion events (order clicks, phone calls, directions, catering form)
Bounce rate and engagement time
Device breakdown (mobile vs desktop)

What the dashboard DISTRIBUTES based on Website data:

New keyword opportunities → triggers content creation (blog posts, location pages)
Low-CTR pages → triggers title/meta rewrites
High-traffic pages with low conversion → triggers UX fixes
Mobile bounce spikes → triggers mobile optimization tasks
Source attribution → tells you which channels drive orders, where to spend more
Indexing drops → triggers immediate SEO audit

Refresh cadence: Weekly review. Monthly deeper analysis.
Owner: Whoever handles digital (you, agency, VA).

Asset 3: GMB / TripAdvisor / Bing Local
Role: Local discovery layer across the three search engines that matter.
What it FEEDS to the dashboard:
From GMB:

Direction requests by day of week
Calls by day of week
Profile views (Search vs Maps)
Photo views
Top search queries
Popular Times graphs
New reviews + sentiment
Q&A activity

From TripAdvisor:

Ranking position in local restaurants list
New reviews + sentiment
Photo upload activity
Bookmark / save count

From Bing Places:

Listing views
Click-throughs to website
Direction requests
Bing-specific search queries (different demographic than Google: older, often desktop, often higher AOV)

What the dashboard DISTRIBUTES based on local search data:

Day-of-week intent patterns → feeds daily prompt forecasting
Search query gaps (e.g., "catering" searched, no catering revenue) → triggers catering page content + Meta ads
Photo view drops → triggers fresh photo upload
New review notifications → triggers response queue (24-48hr SLA)
Q&A questions → triggers FAQ page updates on website
TripAdvisor ranking shifts → triggers review acquisition pushes
Bing-specific queries → expands keyword targeting

Refresh cadence: Daily quick-check (reviews, Q&A). Weekly deep dive.
Owner: Manager handles daily review responses. Owner/GM does weekly review.

Asset 4: NAP Reconciliation
Role: Data integrity layer. The thing nobody thinks about until it kills your local rankings.
What it FEEDS to the dashboard:

Citation accuracy score across 30+ directories
Mismatched listings flagged
Duplicate listings flagged
Missing listings flagged
Schema/sameAs implementation status on website

What the dashboard DISTRIBUTES based on NAP data:

Citation cleanup queue (prioritized: Tier 1 / Tier 2 / Tier 3)
Schema markup updates needed
sameAs array updates when new social profiles get added
Duplicate listing removal tasks
Bing/Apple Maps/Yelp sync issues

The canonical NAP record (the single source of truth):
Chicho's Peruvian Charcoal Chicken
6300-2 Annapolis Rd, Ste 2
Hyattsville, MD 20784
(301) 501-5771
chichoschicken.com
This lives in the dashboard as the master record. Every channel pulls from it. Any deviation gets flagged.
Refresh cadence: Monthly audit. Real-time monitoring via tool (Moz Local, BrightLocal, or Yext).
Owner: SEO contractor or you. Set-and-forget once cleaned, but needs monthly verification.

Asset 5: Social Media + Nextdoor
Role: Awareness and community layer. Where you build brand and reach people not actively searching.
What it FEEDS to the dashboard:
From TikTok / Instagram / Facebook:

Post performance (views, likes, shares, comments, saves)
Follower growth rate
Profile visit rate from posts
Link clicks from bio
Top performing content themes
Comment sentiment

From Nextdoor:

Post reach by neighborhood
Engagement (likes, comments, shares)
Recommendations earned
Direct messages received
Neighborhood click-throughs

What the dashboard DISTRIBUTES based on social data:

Top-performing content → repurposed across channels and into Meta ad creative
Underperforming content → flagged for kill or pivot
Engagement spikes → triggers immediate response (the "comment within 2 hrs" rule for viral moments)
Nextdoor neighborhood gaps → expand posting radius or run Nextdoor ads in weak zones
Best post times by platform → adjusts posting schedule
Comment sentiment shifts → flags potential brand issues

The asset queue: From the 50-video TikTok batch + ongoing photo shoots + weekly content production. Each asset gets distributed to:

TikTok (primary post)
Instagram Reels (same day)
Facebook Reels (same day)
YouTube Shorts (next day)
GMB posts (curated weekly)
Nextdoor (selective, only the most local-relevant)
Meta ads (top performers become paid creative)
Email newsletters (best content embedded weekly)

Refresh cadence: Daily posting. Weekly performance review.
Owner: Content lead (you, contractor, or in-house if you have one).

Asset 6: Email
Role: Owned audience layer. The highest-margin channel because every send costs nearly zero.
What it FEEDS to the dashboard:

List size + growth rate
Open rates by campaign
Click rates by campaign
Conversion rates (email → order)
Revenue attributed to email
Segment performance (VIPs vs lapsed vs new)
Unsubscribe rate
Birthday capture rate

What the dashboard DISTRIBUTES based on email data:

Weekly send queue (Tuesday blast + segment-specific sends)
Triggered automation status check (welcome series, birthday, win-back, post-purchase)
List hygiene flags (high bounce rate, low engagement segments)
A/B test results → applies winning formats forward
Capture rate shortfalls → triggers re-training of in-store staff on email-ask script
Best subject lines → reused across SMS and social
Top-performing offers → become Meta ad creative

The automation flows running in background:

Welcome series (3 emails over 14 days)
Post-purchase thank you + review request
Birthday week free dessert
60-day win-back ($5 off)
90-day deep win-back ($10 off + free side)
VIP appreciation (top 10% spenders, monthly exclusive offer)
Catering follow-up (90 days post-event)

Refresh cadence: Weekly Tuesday send. Automations run continuously.
Owner: You or a marketing VA.

Asset 7: Rewards Platform
Role: Retention layer. Turns one-time customers into regulars.
What it FEEDS to the dashboard:

Member count + growth rate
Member vs non-member AOV
Visit frequency by member tier
Points earned vs redeemed
Most popular reward redemptions
Inactive member count (haven't earned/redeemed in 60+ days)
Referrals generated (if program supports it)

What the dashboard DISTRIBUTES based on rewards data:

Member-only offers via email/SMS
Tier upgrade celebrations (you just hit Gold!)
Inactive member win-back triggers
Referral push campaigns
Reward redemption insights → guides menu development (what people actually want for free tells you what they value)
Member exclusive events → feeds Asset 10 (Events)

Setup: Toast Loyalty as the foundation. Optionally layered with Marsello, Thanx, or Spendgo for deeper automation.
Refresh cadence: Monthly performance review. Real-time triggers.
Owner: Auto-managed mostly. Monthly check-in.

Asset 8: Food Apps (DoorDash / Uber Eats / Grubhub)
Role: Third-party demand layer. High-cost, high-volume channels that need active management.
What it FEEDS to the dashboard:
From each platform:

Sales by week
Order count by week
AOV per platform
Items sold ranking
Conversion rate (impressions → orders)
Sponsored Listing performance + ROAS
Promo redemption rates
Customer review trends per platform

What the dashboard DISTRIBUTES based on food app data:

Cross-platform performance comparison → reallocate ad spend to best ROAS
Underperforming menu items → photo refresh, description rewrite, or kill
Top items per platform → ensure they stay top of menu listing
Promo expiration alerts → renewal queue
Direct-order migration → printed inserts in every third-party app order
Commission cost vs sales → margin analysis monthly
Review trends per app → tier-specific response priority

Refresh cadence: Weekly per platform. Monthly cross-platform review.
Owner: GM or you, depending on volume.

Asset 9: Reviews Intel Dashboard
Role: Voice-of-customer aggregator. Pulls all reviews from all platforms into one place.
What it FEEDS to the dashboard:
Aggregated review data from:

Google Business Profile
Yelp
TripAdvisor
DoorDash
Uber Eats
Grubhub
Facebook
Nextdoor recommendations
Restaurantji
Toast reviews (if enabled)

For each review:

Platform
Star rating
Date
Theme/topic mentioned (auto-tagged: food quality, service, speed, cleanliness, value, specific menu items)
Sentiment (positive / neutral / negative)
Response status (responded / not yet)
Response time

What the dashboard DISTRIBUTES based on review intel:

Daily response queue (sorted by urgency: 1-2 star = today, 3 star = within 48 hrs, 4-5 star = within 5 days)
Theme alerts → operational fixes (e.g., "wait time" mentioned in 4 reviews this week → throughput audit)
Hero product confirmation → marketing campaign triggers (e.g., "yellow sauce" praised in 8 reviews → TikTok video, GMB post, Meta ad creative)
Staff recognition → who got named positively (training reinforcement)
Negative pattern alerts → owner gets pinged when 3+ negative reviews share a theme in 30 days
Review velocity tracking → if reviews slow down, capture system needs attention
Cross-platform sentiment comparison → e.g., DoorDash reviews trending negative while in-store positive = delivery issue, not food issue

Tools to power this: Birdeye, Podium, Reputation, Reviewshake, or even a manual Google Sheet aggregator if budget is tight. The goal is one inbox, not 10 separate apps to check.
Refresh cadence: Daily review check. Weekly theme analysis. Monthly trend report.
Owner: Manager handles responses. Owner reviews trends weekly.

Asset 10: Events (Customer Day) → Eventbrite + Facebook Events + Luma
Role: Community + acquisition layer. Brings people through the door for a reason beyond food.
What it FEEDS to the dashboard:

Event RSVPs per platform
Attendance vs RSVP conversion rate
Source of attendees (which platform drove them)
Spend per event attendee
Repeat attendance (did they come back?)
Email captures from event signups
Social share rate of event posts

What the dashboard DISTRIBUTES from each event:
When an event is created in the dashboard, it auto-distributes to:

Eventbrite listing (broader reach, search-friendly)
Facebook Event (community + RSVP function)
Luma (newer, professional crowd, good for catering targets)
GMB Post (local search)
Nextdoor Post (neighborhood)
Email blast to list
SMS announcement
Instagram + TikTok content
Website /events page
In-store signage (table tents, window decals)

Event types to run:
Customer Day (monthly): Themed appreciation day. "Peruvian Independence Day Brunch" / "Family Sunday" / "Spice Lovers Tasting." Free starter for first 50 customers. Photo-friendly setup. Drives repeat visits.
Catering Showcase (quarterly): Invite-only tasting for businesses, churches, schools, HOAs within 5 miles. Catered samples, menu booklet, business cards. One showcase = 5-15 catering accounts typically.
Pop-Up Themed Nights (bi-weekly): Live music night, ladies' night, family movie night, sports viewing. Drives slow-day traffic.
Cooking Class / Demo (quarterly): How to make Peruvian sauces, the rotisserie process. Ticketed via Eventbrite. $15-25 entry. Drives social content + customer affinity.
What the dashboard tracks per event:

ROI: cost vs revenue + email captures + repeat visits attributed
Best-performing event types → repeat
Best-performing channels per event → reallocate promotion

Refresh cadence: Monthly event creation. Real-time RSVP tracking.
Owner: You or a marketing lead.

